close_symbols: (macros used to size name arrays, e.g. OS_MAX_API_NAME)
explanation:
- OS_timebase_prop_t: Required to know the exact size and layout of timebase_prop (in particular the length and type of the member timebase_prop->name) so the sizeof(timebase_prop->name) expression and the memset call can be evaluated for out‑of‑bounds writes.
- OS_common_record_t: Required to determine the type and size of record->name_entry (the source passed to strncpy) so the analysis can determine whether strncpy may read beyond the source object bounds.
- OS_timebase_internal_record_t: Included because the function reads fields from this struct; while not directly a string, its layout confirms which members are accessed and helps ensure no aliasing/overlap that could affect buffer bounds assumptions.
- OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET: Macro/inline used to obtain record and timebase pointers from the object token. Needed to confirm the resulting pointer types are indeed OS_common_record_t* and OS_timebase_internal_record_t* and that no pointer arithmetic/aliasing changes the effective buffer bounds.
- OS_global_timebase_table and OS_timebase_table: Definitions/types of the tables accessed via OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET to validate where the name_entry buffer lives and its allocated size/lifetime.
- (macros used to size name arrays, e.g. OS_MAX_API_NAME): Any compile-time macros used to size name_entry or timebase_prop->name must be known to compare source and destination buffer sizes precisely.
- OS_ObjectIdGetById: Prototype and behavior (including what token refers to) and its return values are needed to know when the code actually performs the strncpy (i.e., only on OS_SUCCESS) and to ensure the token maps to valid table entries.
- OS_SUCCESS: Constant value used to check the result of OS_ObjectIdGetById; required to reason about control flow and whether the copy executes.
- OS_CHECK_POINTER: Macro/inline that checks timebase_prop — needed to ensure the function returns on NULL and that subsequent dereferences (memset/strncpy) operate on valid pointers.
- strncpy: The standard behavior of strncpy (how many bytes are read/written and that it does not necessarily NUL-terminate) must be considered when assessing whether the call can read/write out of bounds and whether the destination can end up unterminated.

These symbols provide the information necessary to determine (1) the source buffer size and lifetime, (2) the destination buffer size, and (3) the control flow that governs whether the copy occurs — all required to check for any accesses beyond object bounds per the MISRA rule.
